            <div class="content-section">
                <h2>
                    <span><i class="fa-solid fa-book-open section-icon"></i> What You Will Learn</span>
                </h2>
                <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                    <p>This topic focuses on the design and querying of single-table databases:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Database Structure:</strong> Understanding Fields (columns), Records (rows), and the
                            concept of a Flat-File database.</li>
                        <li><strong>Data Types:</strong> Choosing the correct type for data (Text, Integer, Real,
                            Boolean, Date/Time).</li>
                        <li><strong>Primary Keys:</strong> The crucial role of a unique identifier to distinguish every
                            record.</li>
                        <li><strong>SQL (Structured Query Language):</strong> Writing scripts to Select, Filter, Order,
                            and Count data.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Section 9.1 Collapsible -->
            <details class="content-section" id="9.1">
                <summary>
                    <h3>
                        <span><i class="fa-solid fa-table-columns topic-icon"></i> 9.1 Database Concepts</span>
                        <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down toggle-icon"></i>
                    </h3>
                </summary>

                <div class="section-body">
                    <h4>What you need to know:</h4>

                    <div class="learning-points">
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Definition:</strong> Define a single-table database from given data storage
                                requirements.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Structure:</strong> Understand the meaning of:
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Field:</strong> A single category of data (a column).</li>
                                    <li><strong>Record:</strong> A complete set of data for one item (a row).</li>
                                    <li><strong>Validation:</strong> Rules to ensure data entered is reasonable.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Data Types:</strong> Suggest suitable basic data types:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Text/Alphanumeric</li>
                                    <li>Character</li>
                                    <li>Boolean</li>
                                    <li>Integer</li>
                                    <li>Real</li>
                                    <li>Date/Time</li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Primary Key:</strong> Understand the purpose of a primary key and identify a
                                suitable primary key for a given database table.
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Nested Notes Collapsible -->
                    <details class="notes-box">
                        <summary>
                            <h4>
                                <span><i class="fa-solid fa-lightbulb"></i> Notes & Guidance</span>
                                <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down toggle-icon"></i>
                            </h4>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="notes-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Single Table:</strong> For IGCSE, we focus on "Flat File" databases (just
                                    one table), not complex relational databases with foreign keys.</li>
                                <li><strong>Primary Key:</strong> Must be unique for every record. Examples:
                                    <code>StudentID</code>, <code>VehicleReg</code>, <code>ISBN</code>. Never use names
                                    (people can have the same name).</li>
                                <li><strong>Data Types:</strong>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li><em>Text:</em> "John", "CV34 5HT" (Phone numbers are text!).</li>
                                        <li><em>Real:</em> 12.99, 3.14 (Numbers with decimals).</li>
                                        <li><em>Boolean:</em> True/False, Yes/No.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                </div>
            </details>

            <!-- Section 9.2 Collapsible -->
            <details class="content-section" id="9.2">
                <summary>
                    <h3>
                        <span><i class="fa-solid fa-magnifying-glass topic-icon"></i> 9.2 Structured Query Language
                            (SQL)</span>
                        <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down toggle-icon"></i>
                    </h3>
                </summary>

                <div class="section-body">
                    <h4>What you need to know:</h4>

                    <div class="learning-points">
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Querying:</strong> Read, understand, and complete SQL scripts to query data
                                stored in a single database table.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Commands:</strong> You must be able to use and understand the following
                                commands:
                                <ul>
                                    <li><code>SELECT</code> (specifies the fields to show)</li>
                                    <li><code>FROM</code> (specifies the table)</li>
                                    <li><code>WHERE</code> (specifies the criteria/filter)</li>
                                    <li><code>ORDER BY</code> (sorts the results)</li>
                                    <li><code>DESCENDING</code> / <code>ASCENDING</code></li>
                                    <li><code>SUM</code> (adds up values)</li>
                                    <li><code>COUNT</code> (counts number of records)</li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Operators:</strong> Use logical operators within the <code>WHERE</code> clause:
                                <ul>
                                    <li><code>AND</code></li>
                                    <li><code>OR</code></li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Nested Notes Collapsible -->
                    <details class="notes-box">
                        <summary>
                            <h4>
                                <span><i class="fa-solid fa-lightbulb"></i> Notes & Guidance</span>
                                <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down toggle-icon"></i>
                            </h4>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="notes-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Standard Query Structure:</strong><br>
                                    <code>SELECT Name, Age</code><br>
                                    <code>FROM Students</code><br>
                                    <code>WHERE Age >= 15 AND House = 'Red'</code><br>
                                    <code>ORDER BY Age DESCENDING</code>
                                </li>
                                <li><strong>Wildcard:</strong> <code>SELECT *</code> means "Select ALL fields".</li>
                                <li><strong>Functions:</strong> <code>SELECT COUNT(ID) FROM Students</code> returns a
                                    single number (the total count).</li>
                                <li><strong>Ordering:</strong> The default is usually Ascending, but it is good practice
                                    to specify it explicitly if required.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                </div>
            </details>

            <!-- Exam Expectations -->
            <div class="exam-section">
                <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-pen-to-square section-icon"></i> Exam Expectations: What You Need to Do</h2>
                <p>For the Cambridge IGCSE (0478) exam, you must be able to:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Write SQL:</strong> Write a full SQL query from scratch based on a scenario (e.g., "Show
                        the names of all cars that are Blue and cost more than £10,000").</li>
                    <li><strong>Interpret SQL:</strong> Look at a given SQL script and predict exactly what the output
                        will be (which records will be shown and in what order).</li>
                    <li><strong>Choose Data Types:</strong> Given a sample table of data (e.g., a flight schedule),
                        identify the most appropriate data type for each column (e.g., Arrival Time = Date/Time, Flight
                        Number = Text).</li>
                    <li><strong>Identify Keys:</strong> Select the best field to use as a Primary Key and explain why
                        (uniqueness).</li>
                </ul>
